===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `more` baraye namayesh matn-haye toolani dar safhe-ye terminal estefade mishavad. In dastoor be shoma komak mikonad ke matn ra safhe be safhe bebinid va control konid.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `more +<line_number> <file_name>`  --> 📍 Shoru' az khat-e moshakhas shode.
    🔹 `more -d <file_name>`  --> 📣 Namayesh "Press space to continue, 'q' to quit" be jaye bell sound.
    🔹 `more -c <file_name>`  --> 🧹 Tamiz kardan safhe ghabl az namayesh har safhe jadid.
    🔹 `more -p <file_name>`  --> 📄 Hamishe az avval safhe shoru' kon.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ more file.txt

    🔹 Namayesh `file.txt` safhe be safhe.

    $ more +10 file.txt

    🔹 Namayesh `file.txt` az khat-e dahom.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ more -d logfile.log

    🔹 Agar file toolani bood, be shoma etela' mide ke baraye edame space ra bezanid ya ba 'q' kharej shavid, be jaye sedaye bell annoying.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `more` command is used to view long text files one screen at a time in the terminal. It allows you to control the pace at which the text is displayed.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `more +<line_number> <file_name>`  --> 📍 Start displaying from the specified line number.
    🔹 `more -d <file_name>`  --> 📣 Display "Press space to continue, 'q' to quit" instead of the bell sound.
    🔹 `more -c <file_name>`  --> 🧹 Clear the screen before displaying each new page.
    🔹 `more -p <file_name>`  --> 📄 Always start at the top of the file.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ more file.txt

    🔹 Display `file.txt` one screen at a time.

    $ more +10 file.txt

    🔹 Display `file.txt` starting from line 10.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ more -d logfile.log

    🔹 If the file is long, it informs you to press space to continue or quit with 'q', instead of an annoying bell sound.